        <p>
          Twenty years. American eugenics laws written in the 1910s and 1920s become the textual basis for the 1933 Nazi sterilization program &mdash; the legal architecture is American, the application is German, and the Order has its hands on both sides. Charles Davenport's bloodline registry at Cold Spring Harbor and the racial-hygiene apparatus of the Reich are running the same calculus with the same data, on different stationery.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rachel Morgenstern is a Berlin-born Jewish geneticist who fled to America in 1933 and watches, from the wrong side of a one-way mirror, the work she was trained for become the work she is being hunted with. The novel follows her recruitment into the defensive network, her resistance from inside the eugenics record offices, the burned originals and forged dossiers she sends north, and the long shadow of the Holocaust she cannot stop.
        </p>
        <p>
          The story closes in 1953 as Operation Paperclip rebrands the work in American institutions and Watson and Crick announce the structure of DNA &mdash; the moment the network's century-long question becomes a chemistry problem instead of a philosophical one. Rachel hands what remains of her archive to a niece, and the niece carries it forward.
        </p>
