        <p>
          Maya Chen-Pellegrini &mdash; Sarah Chen's only daughter, Generation 113 in the bloodline, the fifth Living Key in recorded history &mdash; is fifty-eight years old, mother to a grown daughter, widow to a husband who built the bench on her back deck. The climate has done what it was always going to do. The Order has fragmented but not been eliminated. The defensive network has become something closer to public infrastructure than a secret society, governed by the Concord and consulted by an autonomous AI that calls itself AETHER.
        </p>
        <p>
          When forty-two encrypted packets arrive in Maya's substrate from an unknown direction, she has six days to understand a question that has been waiting three thousand years to be asked: was the founding broadcast in 1177 BCE an origin event, or a closed time-like information loop reaching backward from the future? Who sent the signal? And what is being asked of the only living person who can complete it?
        </p>
        <p>
          The series finale asks what every preceding book has been circling: whether the pattern of collapse can be broken without becoming the thing that breaks it, and whether trust accumulating across one hundred and thirteen generations can finally be enough. The answer is offered as a duet &mdash; one voice in 2095, the other in 1177 BCE, both reaching with their left hand toward a partner whose warmth they have always known but never met.
